2. Frisii. These lived always be- tween the Yssel and the lower Ems, and their name is still preserved in that of Friesland. The distinction into ‘maiores’ and ‘minores' (found here alone), may coincide with that of Frisii and Frisiabones in Plin. 4. 15, 29, 101. They are first known as subdued by Drusus, and as in dependence on Rome till their revolt in A.D. 28 (A. 4. 72, 1), then as again reduced by Corbulo in A.D. 47 (A. 11. 19, Ι), and as having joined the revolt of Civilis (H. 4. 15. 4; 79, 35. It is probable (see A. 13, 54) that the eastern portion, coinciding with one of the divisions above given, retained its independence (see Momms. v. E. T. i. 126, note).
